Let me begin with the professionalism and knowledge of Dan Porto, the Energy Consultant that came to our house to tell us about Vivint.  We had been visited a while back by another consultant who didn't follow through at all, and after he visited us we heard negative things ,about solar energy that made us glad he hadn't followed through.  Dan Porto listened very carefully and patiently to our concerns and proceeded to clear up the misinformation we had received and then pointed out all of the positives that solar energy, and Vivint Solar in particular, had to offer.  Then Dan gave us names and addresses of some of our neighbors as references to prove that Vivint already had happy customers right in our neighborhood which helped close the deal.  Dan is very personable and quickly gained our trust.  We needed to have our electrical panel replaced to accommodate the panels that will be installed.  Wayne Mullin and Oscar Ruiz (I believe they were from the Taunton location) were the electricians that arrived to do the electrical panel changeover.  We can't say enough about what hard workers they were.  It was an extremely hot and very humid day, but they worked non-stop from the time that they arrived and never took a break - They were here all day!!!  They finished the job and left our property spotless.  They were efficient, courteous and very friendly.  All in all we had a fantastic experience with Vivint right from the beginning and we've told many of our friends and family members about our experience.  We recommend Vivint very highly and have been telliing others to consider solar and to consider and trust Vivint when they are ready.

My sales representative was amazing. He was very detailed and answered any and all questions I had. He also kept in constant contact with me. My other quote was Trinity. If it was based on customer interaction you would have won hands down. There were several key areas that didn't go in your favor. First off the number of panel's verses watts. You guys came in at 9.36kw with 36 panels while Trinity came in at 27 panels at 10kw. Long term 27 isn't going to fill my roof so I'll have room for expansion if down the line I decide to make a 2nd floor on my house. The 36 doesn't leave very much room to expand. In terms of watts, you guys are 260 per panel while Trinity is 290 per panel. That makes the big difference in kW.  The up front of 10 kW verses 9.36kw is a big plus for me especially for the space being taken up.  Next of course you guys have 9 more panels so you are more expensive for less kW. You are roughly 7000 dollars more which makes you monthly payment higher even though your interest rate was a little bit lower.  Side by side of the warranty's are all comparable except for the inverter. Trinity has a 12 year warranty on the inverter while you have a 10 year. Also I talked to Trinity and I am going to put the inverter on the wall in the house downstairs to really get all the life out of it. A major concern for me as well was your inverter price. I was told $115 for your inverter while Trinity was $1000 which I did a google search and they were more in Trinity's range. The $115 gave me an uneasy feeling of quality. Those were my main reasons for my decision.
